What is Luks ?
1- What is an Encryption : 
First of all, we have to understand what an encryption is.
An encryption is when you have for example a notebook that have :
Password : hunter2
Bank : 123456789
Anyone can read it.
But with an encryption, it becomes something like this :
A81D98D9A72BC9...
F029AC1123…
Nobody understands it without the secret key.
Encryption transforms :
Plaintext → Encryption Algorithm → Cipher text.
Only someone possessing the correct key can reverse the process.

2- What is Disk Encryption :
Disk encryption encrypts an entire storage device.
Instead of encrypting individual files, everything becomes encrypted.
Even free space inside the Disk appears random.
If someone steals the drive, they only see random-looking data.

3- Why LUKS Exists ?
Before LUKS, Linux used plain dm-crypt.
Dm-crypt is a Linux Kernel module.
Problem :
Let us say for example that someone steals the hard drive and plug it into another computer, without LUKS he will be able to see all data inside and get an access to everything.
Solution :
Here comes LUKS which uses Master Key to encrypt everything inside the disk, so when stolen, no plain data would be exposed.

4- Master Key :
Is one important concept.
The question is, does LUKS uses the password to encrypt the entire disk?, in that case, for example if someday I decided to change LUKS password,  then the system has to go through every single file, from decrypting every piece of data using “old_password”, then encrypt the entire thing again using “new_password”.
Here is the catch, LUKS here does this thing instead, it generates a random Master Key which is the one that actually protecting the disk, and not the password. The password here is the one protecting the Master Key and not the entire disk.
For example, the password “MIKE” unlocks the Master Key.
When changing the password, the system does not have to re-encrypt every single file (which could take hours), it only changes how the Master Key is protected.
The Master Key is randomly generated by LUKS. This little piece is called a Metadata.
